Chemotherapeutic drugs can be categorized based on their irritancy into vesicant and irritant drugs (
Table 4
). Vesicant drugs are those that, when extravasated from the vascular route into surrounding tissues, can cause blistering, tissue necrosis, or decay. Vesicant agents typically elicit sensations of burning or stinging upon contact with the body. On the other hand, irritant drugs cause local tissue burns, irritation, or mild inflammation after extravasation but do not directly lead to tissue necrosis (106).
